{"title":"Influent and effluent summary statistics (by plant and pooled; counts in original units)","analysis_comments":"The pooled influent distributions span orders of magnitude across organism groups: bacterial indicators are typically very high in influent (e.g., E. coli median 7.12×10^6 MPN/100 mL; total coliform median 8.39×10^7 MPN/100 mL), while protozoa and viruses are far lower (Giardia median 410 /L; adenovirus median 107 MPN/L). Means are often much higher than medians (notably adenovirus, Cryptosporidium), indicating episodic high-load events.

Effluent statistics reflect strong reductions but also method/MDL censoring effects: coliphage effluent medians are at the MDL (1 PFU/mL) for all plants, consistent with frequent non-detects. BrWo shows very low adenovirus effluent central tendency (median at MDL 0.02 MPN/L), whereas NoWe has a much higher adenovirus effluent mean (45.4 MPN/L), suggesting occasional breakthrough events driving the mean. For Giardia, NoWe’s effluent median (~10 /L) is notably higher than BiSp (~1.45 /L) and BrWo (~4.74 /L), despite similar influent medians—worth checking treatment/disinfection alignment with the UF-based effluent sampling definition.

(See: summary_statistics_influent_effluent_by_plant_pooled.csv)","code_filename":"summary_statistics_table_revision.py","data_filename":"summary_statistics_influent_effluent_by_plant_pooled.csv"}

{"title":"Log removal value (LRV) summary statistics (by plant and pooled)","analysis_comments":"Across all plants, bacterial indicators show the largest LRVs: E. coli and fecal coliform median ~6.5 log10, and total coliform median ~5.6 log10. Protozoa show substantially lower removal (Giardia median 1.9; Cryptosporidium median 2.0), and adenovirus is intermediate with a wide spread (median 3.3; IQR 2.7–5.1), consistent with event-to-event variability and censoring at low effluent values.

Plant comparisons (medians): NoWe shows higher adenovirus LRV (4.4) than BiSp (2.9) and BrWo (3.1), aligning with UV at NoWe vs chlorine at BiSp/BrWo. For protozoa, BiSp has the highest Giardia median LRV (2.9) while NoWe is lowest (1.4); Cryptosporidium medians are closer (1.8–2.4). Coliphage LRVs are relatively consistent (≈3.0–3.7), suggesting they may track physical removal processes more than disinfection performance. Aerobic endospores show the lowest indicator LRV (~1.2–1.5), indicating limited removal relative to other indicators.

(See: log_removal_value_summary_by_plant_pooled.csv)","code_filename":"lrv_summary_table.py","data_filename":"log_removal_value_summary_by_plant_pooled.csv"}
